alize them. By linking culture, nation, and identity, Gómez-Barris shows how those most affected by the legacies of the dictatorship continue to live with the presence of violence in their bodies, in their daily lives, and in the identities they pass down to younger generations.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArtxPolitical aspectszChilexHistoryy20th century. 0aCollective memoryzChile. 4aAnthropology. 4aCultural & Social. 4aSocial Science. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aGomez-Barris, Macarena, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052025584540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094249340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520942493423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520942493/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles